		</apparel>
	</ThingDef>
	<!-- Brodie_Mk1 -->
	<ThingDef ParentName="GreatWarHelmetBaseBrodie">
		<defName>GWH_Mk1_Brodie</defName>
		<label>Mk1 </label>
		<description>Very simmilar to the type B, the "Steel Helmet Mark 1" improved the design by introducing a folded and smaller rim, making the edges more uniform and the overall design mor durable and polished. This was the Pattern also used by the Americans.</description>

		<graphicData>
			<texPath>GreatWarHelmets/Brodie_Mk1/Helm</texPath>
		</graphicData>
		<apparel>
			<wornGraphicPath>GreatWarHelmets/Brodie_Mk1/Helm</wornGraphicPath>
		</apparel>
	</ThingDef>
	<!-- Farina -->
	<ThingDef ParentName="GreatWarHelmetBase">
		<defName>GWH_Farina</defName>
		<label>Farina</label>
		<description>Issued in 1915, the italian farina helmet alongsode the armor was handed to the "death companies" (wire cutters) and Arditi. It had no liner and was worn with the army cap under it for padding. The front layer consisted of 4 layers of nickel-chromium sheet metal. It was replaced by italian made adrians later in the war.</description>
		
