	<!-- M1917 -->
	<ThingDef ParentName="GreatWarHelmetBaseStahlhelm">
		<defName>GWH_M1917_Stahlhelm</defName>
		<label>Stahlhelm M1917</label>
		<description>The M1917 variant of the Stahlhelm. The bell is identical to the M1916, 1.2mm thick nickel-chromium steel weighing 1-1.4 kg depending on the size. It was made in the "Kaltziehverfahren" in wich hot steel is pressed into shape. The Liner in this model uses a sheet metal ring instead of the M1916s leather one to connect the tabs (I have no Idea about the terminology of this). For the chinstrap the Pickelhaube chinstraps were reused. The Horns act as Connectors for the Stirnpanzer and as ventalation. The Austro-Hungarian produced M1917 had the liner bolts put higher to the top instead of the lower skirt of the helmet.</description>

		<graphicData>
			<texPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1917/Helm</texPath>
		</graphicData>
		<apparel>
			<wornGraphicPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1917/Helm</wornGraphicPath>
		</apparel>
	</ThingDef>
	<!-- M1917_Stirnpanzer -->
	<ThingDef ParentName="GreatWarHelmetBaseStahlhelmStirnpanzer">
		<defName>GWH_M1917_Stirnpanzer</defName>
		<label>M1917 Stahlhelm Stirnpanzer</label>
		<description>The M1917 but with the Stirnpanzer attached. The Stirnpanzer was made of 4mm thick nickel-chromium and attached at the breating horns and with a belt around the Helmet. Its weight made it impractical for assaults as the helmet would easily tip forward but it was useful for stationary use like machine gunners or observers having to look over the top often.</description>

		<graphicData>
			<texPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1917_Stirnpanzer/Helm</texPath>
		</graphicData>
		<apparel>
			<wornGraphicPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1917_Stirnpanzer/Helm</wornGraphicPath>
		</apparel>
	</ThingDef>
	<!-- M1917_Visorless -->
	<ThingDef ParentName="GreatWarHelmetBaseStahlhelm">
		<defName>GWH_M1917_Visorless</defName>
		<label>M1917 Stahlhelm Visorless</label>
		<description>Identical to the M1917 but with the visor removed. These Helmets are rumored to have been produced for the ottoman Empire in order to not hinder prayers but this has yet to be proven definitively. Other assumtions include easier operation of Spotting equipment and other actions a visor abov the head would be hindering.</description>

		<graphicData>
			<texPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1917_Visorless/Helm</texPath>
		</graphicData>
		<apparel>
			<wornGraphicPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1917_Visorless/Helm</wornGraphicPath>
		</apparel>
	</ThingDef>
	<!-- M1918 -->
	<ThingDef ParentName="GreatWarHelmetBaseStahlhelm">
		<defName>GWH_M1918_Stahlhelm</defName>
		<label>Stahlhelm M1918</label>
		<description>Identical to the M1917 shell but with added ear cutouts. This was done to improve hearing of orders and so on as well as reduce the ringing caused by a sustained hit. The M1918 was also made without these cutouts. Bouth had the old pickelhaube chinstrap replaced with a new one connected directly to the liner.</description>

		<graphicData>
			<texPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1918/Helm</texPath>
		</graphicData>
		<apparel>
			<wornGraphicPath>GreatWarHelmets/M1918/Helm</wornGraphicPath>
		</apparel>
		<equippedStatOffsets Inherit="false"></equippedStatOffsets>
	</ThingDef>
	<!-- Shovelsteel -->
	<ThingDef ParentName="GreatWarHelmetBaseAdrian">
		<defName>GWH_Shovelsteel</defName>
		<label>Shovelsteel Helmet M17</label>
		<description>The "Sohlberg Helmet" was made of shovelsteel and a simmilar design to the Adrian. It never had an official Name nor a long production run. Intended as the russian Empires main Helmet, material shortages and a revolution cut production short. They saw limited service in the great war but mainly in the russian civil war. I couldn't find concrete stats so the Adrians ones were used as stand in.</description>

		<graphicData>
			<texPath>GreatWarHelmets/Shovelsteel/Helm</texPath>
		</graphicData>
		<apparel>
			<wornGraphicPath>GreatWarHelmets/Shovelsteel/Helm</wornGraphicPath>
		</apparel>
	</ThingDef>
